SATIRE VI.

In this satire Horace attempts to show that real greatness is quite independent of external circumstances3 and that true no- bility consists in personal worth, and not in the distinctions of birth and family. He mentions his own case as a proof that Maecenas selected his friends for their personal qualities‚ since he had no advantages of family to recommend him.
